name: Sia

description.plain:
Sia Kate Isobelle Furler (born December 18, 1975), popularly known as Sia, is an Australian pop singer and songwriter. She is also part of the supergroup, LSD alongside, British singer, Labrinth and American DJ, Diplo. Before her solo debut, Sia also lent vocals to British acid-jazz duo, Zero 7.

Her album 1000 Forms of Fear was released in 2014 and is her most successful album to date, with the top 10 single “Chandelier.”

After performing for nearly 15 years at night clubs as well as releasing five studio albums, Sia took a hiatus from performing in 2010 when she began writing for other artists. Some of her most successful collaborations are “Titanium” with David Guetta, “Diamonds” with Rihanna and “Wild Ones” with Flo Rida.

Sia famously started hiding her face during her recent promotional cycles and public events. She has stated that because when she started to become a little bit famous, it felt destabilizing for her in some ways. In order for her to maintain a certain amount of privacy, she focused on writing for other artists and started covering up her face with the famous wig.

Sia has the most music videos with over a billion views on YouTube of all-female artists, with 5 videos having reached at least one billion views.

She has received a wide range of awards, including a total of 8 Grammy nominations. Sia also has had 8 of her songs go double platinum in record sales.

She continues to remain a force to be reckoned with and a powerhouse singer-songwriter in the entire music industry.

songs.title: Chandelier

body.plain:
“Chandelier” was released as the lead single from Sia’s sixth studio album, 1000 Forms Of Fear. Despite its soaring melody, the song has a sad theme describing the life of a “party girl”. On the track, Sia talks about her alcohol and drug addiction.

Sia has written songs for pop stars like Rihanna, Katy Perry, and Britney Spears, but this time she saves the “swing from the chandelier” moment for her own angelic voice.

The song has been described by many as Sia’s breakthrough performance due to its huge commercial success and critical acclaim. Billboard named the track one of the most memorable choruses of all time.

Maddie Ziegler revealed in a YouTube video that the people on set said that the set was haunted, due to the building being very old. Being an eleven year old, she was scared to dance there on her own. Maddie also said that when Sia reached out to her, asking her to be in the music video, she thought she would be a back-up dancer:

But when I got on set, it was just me in rehearsal.

songs.title: Cheap Thrills

body.plain:
“Cheap Thrills” was originally written for Rihanna’s album ANTi. The song was rejected and later included on Sia’s This Is Acting—an album that is comprised entirely of songs Sia wrote for other people.

The song was released as a promotional single on December 16, 2015.

In an interview with Rolling Stone, Sia explained why Rihanna passed on the song, saying:

I realized just as soon as I was cutting it that it sounded a little bit too Brit-pop for her. It’s more Icona Pop.

The song is tropical flavored with EDM influences much like Rihanna’s past works.

On February 12, 2016, a remixed version of the song featuring Jamaican hip-hop artist, Sean Paul was released as the second single off the album. That single went on to become Sia’s first #1 song on Billboard Hot 100 chart as a lead artist.

The solo version of Cheap Thrills went on to become the most streamed song by a female artist in Spotify history.

songs.title: Helium

body.plain:
“Helium” is a song written and performed by Sia for the soundtrack of the movie Fifty Shades Darker

Unlike her past collaboration for the first movie, in which she used her lower range and whispery vocals like on her past works such as “Breathe Me”, Sia’s voice in “Helium” is clear and present over an instrumental with orchestral arrangement and vibrant harmonies.

The lyrics feature Sia’s signature empowerment sound, expressing how the love of a partner can help one overcome tough situations, lifting one up the way helium does with a balloon.

On 25th January 2018, a new remix of “Helium” featuring David Guetta and Afrojack was released to be featured in Sia’s MAC Cosmetics x VIVA GLAM campaign.

songs.title: Elastic Heart (Hunger Games Version)

body.plain:
Maddie Ziegler (from the “Chandelier” video) and Shia LaBeouf star in the clip for “Elastic Heart,” directed by Daniel Askill and choreographed by Ryan Heffington.



Additional vocals by The Weeknd appear on The Hunger Games: Catching Fire Original Motion Picture Soundtrack, but not in the album and video version, which was released as the second single from 1000 Forms of Fear.

The video was met with what CNN described as “outrage.” Apparently, the sight of a 28 year-old man and a 12 year-old girl wearing flesh-colored outfits and grappling in a giant bird cage made people uncomfortable, despite the lack of any graphic violence or sexual acts in the video. Barbara Ellen defended the rights of Sia and her collaborators to make provocative art in the Guardian:

Is this where we are now: society flinching from the sight of a man and a girl performing together in any way that hasn’t been entirely emotionally neutered?

Sia was braced for the video’s impact, as she made clear through Twitter, while also trying to make clear the intent of the casting:

https://twitter.com/Sia/status/553023264646123520

https://twitter.com/Sia/status/553023400327647234

Although many have interpreted the video as a depiction of a tumultuous relationship between a girl and her father, Sia and LaBeouf, who came up with the concept for the video, describe it as dueling self-states. The cage acts as a symbol for the human skull, in which the two states do battle.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iVJtWWH2qWk

“Elastic Heart” appears on both The Hunger Games: Catching Fire Original Motion Picture Soundtrack and 1000 Forms of Fear.

body.plain:
Soulful “Bird Set Free” was written by Sia and Tobias Jesso Jr. for Adele, and it sounds like it. The song was also offered to Rihanna at one point, but she (obviously) declined. Sia said “I had seller’s remorse with ‘Bird Set Free’ every time it went away and then came back. The truth is that we wrote ‘Bird Set Free’ for Pitch Perfect 2. They rejected it and took another song of ours called ‘Flashlight’. That became a big thing through the movie, but I could not believe they rejected ‘Bird Set Free’ because to me it was such a big, anthemic, fun, sing-along-in-the-car song.” Then it was intended to appear on 25, it was ultimately deemed unsuitable, and so Sia nabbed it for herself. The track is dominated by an extended metaphor: comparing living in an abusive relationship to being a mistreated captive bird.

It is to be the second single from Sia’s 2016 album This Is Acting, which is comprised of songs that Sia wrote for Adele, Beyonce, Rihanna and others. The song was released on the 3rd of November, the day after This Is Acting was announced.

On November 7, 2015, Sia performed on Saturday Night Live, when Donald Trump was hosting the show.

body.plain:
“Breathe Me” is the lead single from Sia’s third studio album Colour the Small One. It’s a sad, orchestral ballad about being in depression and needing a friend for comfort.

Sia told ilikemusic.com about recording this track:

It always felt like a good song that one. Sam and Felix had put the drums and bass down, they played it all live together one night after they’d been to dinner, and I was really sick with flu and I walked in the next day and the track was there without me singing on it and it was just so sleek. I don’t really listen to my own music. I don’t think most people listen to their own music after they’ve recorded it. Some of my musician friends get really anal and listen to it all the time, analyzing it. But once I’ve done it, I listen to it once and put it to bed, but with that one I was like, “yeah! Again! Again!”

“Breathe Me” introduced Sia to the United States, years before her smash single “Chandelier”. It received attention after being used for the finale of Six Feet Under. It continued to pop up on television over the years, including: Veronica Mars, The Hills, Orange Is the New Black, and even a Coca-Cola commercial for the 2010 Winter Olympics.

The music video was shot in a London theme hotel and was composed from 2500+ Polaroid stills.

body.plain:
Originally written for Rihanna’s album ANTi, “Reaper” was later scrapped. Sia talked about the process with Rolling Stone Magazine:

They’ll entice me into a session by saying, “Rihanna will definitely be there” or “Kanye will definitely be there,” but it’s hilarious because I turn up and, almost always, they never come. So I went into the studio to write for Rihanna with Kanye and neither of them showed up and stayed for less than an hour. They had two tracks. They told me what they had wanted. There were notes from Kanye, and I can’t even remember what they were. I remember I just raced in and raced out, and I thought there was something about the chorus that seemed fun about this song.

Sia continued to talk about the track with Rolling Stone, stating she doesn’t have strong feelings for the song:

I don’t care about the song. I know in print that will look bad, but what I mean is I’m not emotionally attached to it. I thought it was a fun song. I think it’s a good, fun song, but I didn’t anticipate it being on the record. But my manager really likes it so I put it on for him.

body.plain:
“Move Your Body” was released as the 4th single off of This Is Acting . Sia revealed during a radio interview with 103.7 KVIL in November 2015 that “Move Your Body” was intended for Shakira. Move Your Body is a stuttering dance floor magnet.

Sia has stated in her interview with Rolling Stone magazine,

One of them is a Shakira reject, which there’s no doubt when you hear it. You’ll know that it was a Shakira reject because I sound like Shakira.

Sia worked with Shakira on the song “https://genius.com/Shakira-chasing-shadows-lyrics” for her eponymous album in 2014. Sia also co-wrote “Try Everything”, the theme song for Disney’s Zootopia, also sung by Shakira. The harmonizing in the Intro and Post Chorus is very similar to Shakira’s style of singing.

Sia performs the song as a part of her tour setlist.



A remix of the song featuring Alan Walker was added on the deluxe reissue of This Is Acting.

On January 6th 2016, Sia released a stand-alone ‘Single mix’ of the song.

songs.title: Satisfied

body.plain:
“Satisfied” is a cover by Sia, recorded for the Lin-Manuel Miranda curated Hamilton Mixtape. It features guest appearances from Queen Latifah and Miguel.

The track was originally performed by Renée Elise Goldsberry, who played the role of Angelica in the original Broadway cast. Though Sia stylistically reinterprets the track in places, sometimes subtly changing the lyrics, the song remains a fairly standard cover.

It includes all references to the context in which the song is intended – Kelly Clarkson’s cover of “It’s Quiet Uptown” notably removed specific references to the show’s overarching narrative.

body.plain:
“To Be Human” is an anthemic song with a cinematic build up recorded by Australian artist Sia for the Original Soundtrack of the 2017 movie, Wonder Woman. It features English singer-songwriter, Labrinth.

On the song, Sia and Labrinth sing about what it truly means to be a human. The song directly relates to Gal Gadot’s character, Diana Prince, who is not a ‘human’ but has to adjust to the life of a human. Towards the end of the movie, Wonder Woman aka Diana Prince chooses love over hatred.

The song was released ahead of the film’s release on June 2, 2017.
